{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632725"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:44:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:44:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17438"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17438"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10128"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70822"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10128"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56288"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5512"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23809"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70822"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EQuality improvement methodology is used to systematically enhance healthcare delivery and patient outcomes. One widely used approach involves testing changes on a small scale before broader implementation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct sequence of steps in a quality improvement cycle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Act-Plan-Do-Study","Study-Plan-Do-Act","Plan-Do-Study-Act","Do-Plan-Study-Act","Plan-Study-Do-Act"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EPlan-Do-Study-Act (PDSA)\u003C/strong\u003E cycle is the correct sequence for quality improvement projects. This systematic approach involves:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlan: Identify an opportunity and plan for change\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDo: Implement the change on a small scale\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStudy: Analyse the results and learn from the outcomes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAct: Refine the change based on learnings\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect sequences can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStudy-Plan-Do-Act\u003C/strong\u003E - one cannot study outcomes before planning and implementing a change.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDo-Plan-Study-Act\u003C/strong\u003E - implementation should not occur before proper planning has taken place.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAct-Plan-Do-Study\u003C/strong\u003E - one cannot take action before understanding the problem and reviewing results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlan-Study-Do-Act\u003C/strong\u003E - one cannot study outcomes before implementing a change.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe PDSA cycle is iterative, meaning it can be repeated multiple times to continuously refine and improve processes. Starting with small-scale tests allows for learning and adaptation before wider implementation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Plan-Do-Study-Act cycle is a systematic method for testing changes in quality improvement projects.","Quality improvement projects should start with small-scale tests before wider implementation.","Data collection and 